# Introduction
The Gefieder image is multi-tenant / team data analytics platform built on top of 
PostgreSQL, DuckDB, SQLMesh and Django (with Unfold admin interface).


## Instructions

Compute a django secret key for django (the last dash is not a typo, it tells podman to 
read the secret from stdin):
```bash
openssl rand -hex 265 | podman secret create django_secret_key -
```
You may receive a warning like `"/" is not a shared mount`. This is expected and can be 
ignored. The key will remain immutable. You cannot overwrite it using the same command 
again. You have to call `podman secret rm django_secret_key` first and then use the above 
command again to create a new one.

Create a managed secret for the PostgreSQL password as well. With the version below,
you will be prompted to enter the password interactively without showing it on
screen.
```bash
read -s PW && printf "%s" "$PW" | podman secret create postgres_password -
```
If the secret already exists, remove it first with `podman secret rm postgres_password`.


Build the image from the repository root:

```bash
podman build -t gefieder .
```



Run the container with the application and PostgreSQL exposed:

```bash
podman run -d \
  --name gefieder \
  --replace \
  --secret django_secret_key \
  --secret postgres_password \
  -p 8000:8000 \
  -p 5432:5432 \
  gefieder
```

If the container is already using the same ports, stop or remove the old one first:

```bash
podman rm -f gefieder
```

Connect to the running services:

- Open the Django application at http://localhost:8000/
- Connect to PostgreSQL with:

```bash
psql -h localhost -p 5432 -U postgres -d postgres
```

When prompted for a password, use the same value that was stored in the `postgres_password` secret (for example, `duckdb`).